iversity of subjects and approaches but also identifies the most salient traits of literature and literary studies today. Leading literary critics and historians offer thought-provoking arguments as well as authoritative explorations of the key terms of literary studies providing students as well as scholars with a rich resource for exploring theoretical issues from a historically informed perspective.Key FeaturesOrganised around the key terms used in literary studies today: archive, book, medium, translation, subjects, senses, animals, objects, politics, time, invention, event, generation, period, beauty, mimesis, style, popular and genrePuts literary history at the forefront of theoretical and methodological reflection in literary studiesOriginal chapters by leading literary critics, theorists and historians"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAyers, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeebee, Thomas O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBru, Sascha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Bruyn, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDe Bruyn, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelville, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDelville, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolsom, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlover, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCracken, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r